Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 12 - Observations¶

Numerical Correlations

Visualizing the correlations using a heatmap and pair plot revealed weak relationships between the numerical variables in the dataset. The correlations range from -0.01 to 0.04, which are very close to zero, indicating an absence of statistically significant linear relationships.

Cuisine and Cost of Order

French cuisine is the most expensive option, boasting both the highest median and mean order prices.

On the other hand, Vietnamese cuisine offers the most budget-friendly meals, with half of its orders costing $12.13 or even less.

Mediterranean food stands out for its higher price range. It holds the record for the highest order value, and a significant number of its orders fall within the upper price range, suggesting a larger portion of their menu items fall within a pricier category.

Cuisine and Prep Time

The analysis of food preparation times reveals variations across different cuisines. Korean cuisine stands out for its speed, boasting both the fastest average and median preparation times of 25.5 and 25 minutes, respectively. This makes it a compelling choice for customers seeking a quick meal.

In contrast, Southern cuisine requires a longer wait time, averaging 27.6 minutes per order.

Chinese and Japanese cuisines exhibit similar preparation times, averaging around 27.5 minutes.

Finally, Italian and Thai cuisine have a slightly higher median preparation times of 28 minutes.

Cuisine and Day of the Week

The examination of order data by day of the week reveals interesting trends in cuisine preferences. American cuisine enjoys widespread popularity, consistently ranking first in terms of orders placed on both weekdays and weekends. Japanese cuisine exhibits similar appeal, securing the second-highest number of orders across both days. Spanish cuisine has the lowest weekday orders, and Vietnamese has the lowest weekend orders.

Cuisine and Delivery Time

The analysis reveals variations in delivery times across different cuisines. Vietnamese cuisine stands out for having the slowest average delivery time, clocking in at approximately 26 minutes. Conversely, Korean cuisine boasts the fastest delivery, with both an impressive average and median time of 21 and 20 minutes respectively. This makes Korean food a desirable choice if speedy delivery is a priority.

It's important to acknowledge that several factors can influence delivery speed beyond cuisine type. These include the specific restaurant chosen, the customer's location, the time of day the order is placed, and the complexity of the order itself.

Day of Week and Delivery Time

An interesting insight emerges from analyzing delivery times by day of the week. Despite having fewer orders overall, weekdays experience slightly longer delivery times compared to weekends. The average delivery time on weekends is nearly 6 minutes faster. This finding suggests that factors beyond order volume may influence delivery speed. These could include factors like traffic congestion patterns that differ between weekdays and weekends, or potentially a higher concentration of delivery staff working during peak weekend hours.

Day of Week and Cost of Order

The analysis of order cost reveals a consistent trend across weekdays and weekends. This is a noteworthy observation, as one might anticipate higher prices during weekends due to potentially increased demand. This finding suggests that restaurants may employ consistent pricing strategies regardless of the day of the week.

Food Prepartion time and Day of Week

Examination of food preparation times revealed no statistically significant difference between weekdays and weekends. On average, both weekdays and weekends saw an approximate food preparation time of 27 minutes. This suggests that factors other than day of the week may primarily influence preparation speed.

Cuisine Type and Rating

Our analysis indicates a potential trend between cuisine type and customer ratings. Spanish cuisine boasts the highest average rating (4.8%), while Vietnamese cuisine received the lowest average rating (4.0%). However, it's important to acknowledge limitations in the data that make it difficult to draw definitive conclusions.

Sample sizes for both Spanish (6 ratings) and Vietnamese cuisine (5 ratings) are very small, limiting the generalizability of these findings. A significant portion (~39%) of the rating values are missing, introducing uncertainty into the analysis.

It's worth noting that only Mediterranean and Vietnamese cuisine types have orders rated with 3 stars, while all other cuisines received at least a 4-star rating. This observation might be due to factors unrelated to cuisine type itself.

Future investigations with a larger dataset and a reduced number of missing values would be necessary to confirm these initial observations and draw more robust conclusions about the relationship between cuisine type and customer ratings.

Rating and Food Prep time

While a faint trend emerges when visualizing the data using a point plot, a statistically significant correlation between customer ratings and food preparation times is not readily apparent. The average prep time remains consistent across all ratings, hovering around 27.4 minutes. Interestingly, orders with a 3-star rating exhibit the greatest variability in prep time, ranging from approximately 26.8 to 28 minutes. Further investigation with a larger dataset might be necessary to solidify or disprove this initial observation.

Rating and Delivery Time

Examining the relationship between delivery time and rating using a point plot, we see a slight trend of faster delivery times associated with ratings of 3 and 4. However, this trend weakens for ratings of 5. Notably, the mean delivery times across all ratings range from 23.8 to 24.5 minutes, with a total difference of less than one minute. This suggests minimal practical significance in terms of delivery speed based on customer ratings.

Rating and Cost of Order

Visualizing the data using a point plot suggests a potential association between customer ratings and order cost. Orders with higher costs tend to have slightly higher average ratings, with ratings of 3, 4, and 5 falling within a range of approximately \$16 to \$17. This finding could be interpreted in a few ways:

  • Customers might be more satisfied with pricier meals, potentially due to higher quality ingredients or larger portion sizes.
  • Alternatively, restaurants with higher-rated menu items might also set higher prices, creating a correlation without necessarily implying causation

df_ratings = df_ratings.groupby('restaurant_name')[['rating']].agg(['count', 'mean']).reset_index()

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Question 17: Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Conclusions:¶

The Foodhub dataset that has 1,898 food delivery order records. The dataset contained order data from 178 different restaurants. Restaurants were categorized by Cuisine Type, and the were 14 unique cuisine types. This analysis aimed to understand ordering trends and customer preferences within the Foodhub dataset, examining factors like cuisine type, day of the week, cost, customer behavior, and delivery time.

There were no significant relationships between the numerical values like cost_or_order and food_prep and delivery_time, so I had to investigate the dataset further and analyze the relationship between categorial and numerical data.

Cuisine Type Observations

American cuisine reigns supreme in terms of popularity, accounting for over 30% of all orders, followed by Japanese and Italian cuisine. See table below:

index cuisine_type proportion
0 American 30.77
1 Japanese 24.76
2 Italian 15.70
3 Chinese 11.33
4 Mexican 4.06
5 Indian 3.85
6 Middle Eastern 2.58
7 Mediterranean 2.42
8 Thai 1.00
9 French 0.94
10 Southern 0.89
11 Korean 0.68
12 Spanish 0.63
13 Vietnamese 0.37

Korean cuisine boasts the fastest overall delivery time, while Vietnamese cuisine experiences the slowest deliveries on average.

Spanish and Thai cuisine appear to have the highest average ratings, but caution is needed due to missing data (nearly 39% of ratings are missing).

Day of Week Observations

Weekends see a significant increase in orders compared to weekdays, while also experiencing faster delivery times. This suggests potential factors affecting delivery speed beyond just order volume, such as traffic congestion patterns or delivery staff availability.

Costs of Order Observations

The average order price sits around \$16.50, with weekends and weekdays exhibiting similar average costs. Interestingly, people are not spending more on orders placed on the weekend.

The Minimum order price is: \$ 4.47 (Japanese Cuisine) The Maximum order price is: \$ 35.41 (Mediterranean Cuisine)

French cuisine has both the highest median and mean order prices.

Vietnamese cuisine, on the other hand, is the most budget-friendly option, with half of its orders costing $12.13 or less.

Mediterranean food stands out for its higher priced orders, with the highest maximum prices and a concentration of outliers in the upper price range.

Customer Observations

The dataset contains orders from 1200 unique customers, with repeat customers accounting for 34.67% (having more than one order).

Rating Observations

It's important to note that nearly 39% of the rating values are missing. While the available data suggests an average rating above 4 for all cuisines, caution is needed due to this data incompleteness. There are no customer ratings under 3, and further exploration might be necessary to understand this.

Spanish, Thai and Indian cuisines had the top 3 average ratings respectively.

Vienamese Cuisine has the lowest average rating at 4.0, however, it also had the lowest number or ratings at 5.

Delivery Time Observations

Korean cuisine boasts the fastest delivery time (around 21 minutes), while Vietnamese cuisine takes the longest on average (approximately 26 minutes). Weekday orders take an average of 5.87 minutes longer than weekend orders to deliver. Investigating this further to see if there are enough available delivery drivers on weekdays is recommended.

Revenue Observations

French (\$4.23), Thai (\$4.11) and Southern (\$4.04) Cuisines have the highest net revenue per order respectively.

Vietnamese Cuisine had the lowest average revenue per order at $2.25

The total net revenue for all orders is \$6166.30

Recommendations:¶

Here are some actionable recommendations to improve Foodhub's efficiency and potentially increase revenue based on the analysis:

Delivery Efficiency:

  • Investigate Weekday Delivery Times: Weekdays see longer delivery times despite fewer orders. Analyze if there are enough delivery drivers on weekdays or explore other factors impacting weekday delivery speed.

Customer Acquisition and Retention:

  • Weekday Promotions: Implement targeted promotions to generate more orders and revenue during weekdays when order volume dips.

  • Repeat Customer Incentives: Develop programs or promotions to incentivize repeat customers and increase their order frequency.

Review and Rating System:

  • Investigate Missing Ratings: Explore reasons behind the lack of ratings below 3 and the high percentage of missing ratings (38.77%).

  • Improve Rating App Interface: Review the app's rating system to identify ways to encourage customers to leave reviews and increase overall rating participation.

Revenue Optimization:

  • Minimum Order Consideration: Analyze the feasibility of implementing a minimum order amount to discourage non-profitable orders below $5.

  • Promotions for Higher-Value Orders: Develop targeted promotions that incentivize customers to place orders exceeding $20, considering the higher commission on these orders.

  • Highlight High-Revenue Cuisine Types: Showcase restaurants serving French, Middle Eastern, Southern, Spanish, and Thai cuisines more prominently since they generate higher average revenue per order.

Leveraging Customer Preferences:

  • Need it Fast Category: Create a category on the app highlighting restaurants with the fastest overall preparation and delivery times (like Korean cuisine).

  • Promote Top-Rated Cuisines: Feature cuisine types with high average ratings, such as Spanish and Thai, to attract customers seeking highly-rated options.

Strategic Marketing for Less Popular Cuisines:

  • Promote Vietnamese Cuisine: Vietnamese cuisine has the lowest average ratings and revenue, but removing it might be premature with only 3 restaurants and 7 orders in the dataset. Consider targeted promotions to see if customer interest can be peaked.

  • Budget-Friendly Promotions: Run promotions highlighting Vietnamese cuisine as a budget-friendly option to potentially attract a new customer segment.

Further Analysis:

  • Data Completeness and Granularity: Future analysis with a larger dataset and fewer missing values would be valuable, particularly for solidifying observations around customer ratings. Additionally, exploring factors like specific restaurant locations and menu items could offer deeper insights into customer behavior and revenue generation.
